# Spec Apply Workflow

## Purpose
Implement an approved spec-driven change. Execute tasks from tasks.md in order, write tests, commit atomically, and produce a reviewable pull request. This is phase 2 of 3 in the SDD lifecycle: propose → apply → archive. Requires an approved proposal in `openspec/changes/<change-id>/`.

## Steps to Generate

### 1. Verify Proposal Approval
// if no approved proposal exists
Stop and refer the user to the propose workflow:
- Confirm `openspec/changes/<change-id>/proposal.md` exists
- Confirm tasks.md is present and tasks are not all checked
- Confirm spec deltas describe the intended changes
- If anything is missing, return to propose phase before continuing

### 2. Switch to Feature Branch
// turbo
Ensure work happens on the right branch:
- Check current branch matches the change's feature branch
- Pull latest from base branch and rebase if needed
- Confirm working tree is clean before starting

### 3. Load Change Context
// turbo
Read everything needed to implement correctly:
- Read `proposal.md` (motivation, scope)
- Read `design.md` (technical decisions)
- Read all spec deltas in `openspec/changes/<change-id>/specs/`
- Read `tasks.md` to identify the first uncompleted task

### 4. Implement Tasks Sequentially
For each unchecked task in tasks.md:
- Read the task description carefully
- Implement the minimal code change to satisfy the task
- Write or update tests covering the new behavior
- Run tests for the affected module
- Mark the task complete: change `- [ ]` to `- [x]` in tasks.md
- Commit atomically: `feat: <task-description>` or `fix: <task-description>`
- Reference the change-id in commit body

### 5. Run Full Test Suite
// turbo
After all tasks are checked:
- Run unit tests across the entire codebase
- Run integration tests
- Run linters and static analysis
- All must pass before proceeding

### 6. Verify Spec Compliance
// turbo
Verify implementation matches the spec deltas:
- For each ADDED requirement: confirm at least one test covers each scenario
- For each MODIFIED requirement: confirm old behavior is replaced cleanly
- For each REMOVED requirement: confirm code path is gone, no dead references
- If discrepancies exist, update the deltas (not the code) to reflect reality, or return to propose

### 7. Self-Review the Diff
Read the complete diff as if reviewing someone else's PR:
- No leftover debug code, TODOs, or commented-out blocks
- No hardcoded credentials or sensitive values
- Commit messages follow conventional commits format
- Tests are meaningful, not just coverage padding
- Code matches design.md decisions

### 8. Update tasks.md Final State
If implementation diverged from the original plan:
- Mark added tasks as completed: `- [x] 4.5 Discovered: handle empty input`
- Note skipped tasks with reason: `- [-] 3.2 Skipped: covered by 3.1`
- Keep tasks.md as the source of truth for what was actually built

### 9. Create Pull Request
Open the PR for review:
- Title: `<change-id>: <one-line summary>`
- Description: link `proposal.md`, summarize spec deltas, list verification steps
- Request review from appropriate reviewers
- Mark as ready (not draft) once tests pass

### 10. Address Review Feedback
// if review comments exist
Iterate on feedback:
- Implement requested changes in NEW commits (do not amend during review)
- Update spec deltas if scope changed during review
- Update tasks.md if new tasks emerged
- Re-request review after addressing all comments

## Anti-patterns
- Implementing tasks out of order without justification
- Skipping tests to "save time" — tests are part of the spec
- Force-pushing during active review
- Modifying specs in `openspec/specs/` directly (deltas only until archive)
- Bundling unrelated fixes in the same PR
- Marking tasks as done without actual implementation
- Ignoring failing tests by adding skip annotations
